  <notes>
    **This interface is the contract**. Once Phase 2+ tasks start depending on it, changing it requires coordinated refactor across all consumers. Get the surface right before merging.

    The placeholder impl exists so the BFF compiles cleanly with a complete facade type, but it is NOT registered with DI — by design. Phase 4 (task 040+) will register the real impl. CRUD-side consumers in Phase 5 (task 050+) will depend on the INTERFACE; the DI container will resolve the impl after task 040.

    Do NOT auto-register the facade in this task's PR. The DI registration of `IActionEngineFacade -> ActionEngineFacade` belongs in `AddActionEngineModule.cs` in Phase 4, after the impl has real logic. Registering a NotImplementedException-throwing impl now would make smoke tests pass falsely if any consumer accidentally injects the facade prematurely.

    Coordination with Insights Engine (per `coordination-assessment-with-insights-engine.md`): Insights Engine will call `ResolveGateAsync` to submit gate resolutions on behalf of monitor-triggered actions. The signature here MUST accommodate that — `ResolveGateRequest` includes `gateApprovalId` (Guid), `decision` (Approved | Rejected), `reason` (optional text), `resolvedByUserId` (Guid, optional — null for system/agent decisions).

    The 5 method surface intentionally does NOT include CRUD for Action Definitions or Templates. Those are Phase 4 endpoint concerns (task 040 `ActionEndpoints.cs`), not facade concerns. The facade is the LLM-facing + cross-AI-feature-facing surface.

    If task 014 lands first and modifies `AddActionEngineModule.cs`, this task can land without any conflict — different folders. If this task lands first, task 014 lands without conflict — different folders. Verify clean parallel-land by checking `git status` shows additions only in `Services/Ai/PublicContracts/` for this task and `Services/Ai/ActionEngine/` + `Infrastructure/DI/AddActionEngineModule.cs` + `Program.cs` for task 014.

    The `internal sealed` modifier on the impl class is deliberate. External callers in this assembly can still construct the interface via DI; internal sealed prevents subclassing and forces consumers through the contract.
  </notes>

